1. The Paradox of Permission: When Identity Locks the System
From a physical and legal standpoint, Sir Alex Ferguson has the absolute right to purchase and wear any item of clothing he chooses. Yet within the dimension of identity logic, he possesses no such right at all.

Because "Ferguson" — and his eternal rival "Dalglish" — are no longer merely human beings. They are symbols encoded into the deepest layer of football history and club culture. They are guardians of an Identity Protocol. The moment Ferguson puts on that hostile Liverpool red, or Dalglish puts on the red of Manchester United, the social existence each of them spent a lifetime constructing would face a catastrophic collapse.

This is the nature of identity: it grants the individual a sense of belonging and glory that ordinary life cannot offer — and simultaneously becomes a red jersey prison from which there is no escape.


2. Binary Opposition: The Algorithm That Amputates Reason
When an individual defines themselves as a die-hard supporter of a football club, a nationality, or an ethnic identity, the individual's mind automatically activates a binary opposition algorithm. This algorithm forcibly filters the entire world into a single, ruthless output: us and them.

In this mode, pure reason is crippled. The individual becomes incapable of appreciating the strengths of the opponent, because any achievement by the other side is processed as a direct threat to the value of one's own identity. This inefficient, noise-saturated mode of operation is the root cause of most human conflict and suffering. We walk willingly into the box of our own position, define friend and enemy through a narrow aperture, and compress the vastness of the world into a black-and-white arena.


3. Global Awakening: What Happens When You Remove the Label
And yet — what if we attempted a full-permission Identity Detachment?

When you step down from being the agent of a label and return to a pure, global Human perspective, something shifts. You begin to see that a century of rivalry between two football clubs is simply one expression of humanity's pursuit of competitive beauty. That the conflicts between nations are simply the dynamic process of resource distribution and civilizational evolution.

From the global position, opposition dissolves into a deep stillness. You gain access to genuine reason: no longer driven to anger in defense of a label that was always imaginary, you become capable of appreciating the brilliance of every colour in the world — moved simultaneously by the elegance of one side and the resilience of the other.


4. The Feature, Not the Bug: Irrationality as the Engine of Everything
But here lies the most fascinating paradox: if all of humanity achieved this awakening simultaneously, the game called civilisation would come to an immediate halt.

If every person possessed absolute global rationality — becoming a perfect Glory Hunter, indifferent to outcomes, choosing loyalty only by probability — then matches, competitions, and the entire progress bar of civilisation would lose their meaning. Without that irrational heat, without the emotional fuel of obsession, the system would lose its randomness and grind into stagnation.

The madness and obsession that look like a Bug are, in fact, the core Feature that keeps the system alive.


5. The Art of Switching: How to Hold Both
True wisdom does not lie in erasing identity and becoming an indifferent machine. It lies in mastering the ability to switch between modes.

Inside the arena: throw yourself into the irrational romance of it. Roar for your side. Participate fully in the game called competition.
Outside the arena: switch instantly back to the global observer. Remove the invisible jersey of identity. Meet your opponent with reason and stillness.

We need identity to drive the game. We need the reason that transcends identity to protect the peace. When you can move freely between the obsessed player and the global observer — between full immersion and full detachment — you have truly won the deeper game.








Chapter 3. The Pixel Cage: An Existence Experiment in Voluntary Dimensionality Reduction

1. The Soul Protocol: The Operator as Interface
At the level of base code, Mario is nothing more than a string of binary instructions governing displacement and collision detection. Yet the moment a player presses Start, something changes. A global observer possessing free will formally enters the system.

Mario has no soul of his own. The operator's intervention is Mario's soul. This is what it means to say Soul as an Interface.

Here lies a paradox of permission: the operator possesses a dimensional vantage point that entirely transcends the game world — and yet must voluntarily compress that vantage point into a pixel body wearing a red cap, constrained by a fixed jump height and a finite set of moves. This act of voluntary dimensionality reduction is the only pathway through which a soul can experience the texture of being alive.

You cannot feel the weight of a world you are not inside.


2. The Entropic Arena: Meaning Locked Behind the Timer
When the game enters In-Game mode, the system automatically loads what we might call a pressure algorithm. The countdown timer in the upper corner is a death announcement. The abyss beneath your feet is the collapse of space. The enemies that appear at random are the interference patterns of an indifferent universe.

In this mode, Mario — the soul's vessel — is fragile. System Crash can arrive at any moment.

And yet it is precisely this fragility — the possibility of damage, the scarcity of time — that gives each pixel of movement its weight. Every precise jump matters because an imprecise one ends everything. Pain and threat are the catalysts that convert empty code into meaning.

Remove the risk of death, and heroism becomes nothing more than invalid computation.


3. The Still Sanctuary: Eternal Nothingness in the Selection Menu
In contrast to the lethal terrain of the level, the Selection Menu is a space of absolute rationality and absolute safety. No threat can harm you here. The timer does not run. In theory, you live forever.

This is the closest thing the game has to paradise.

It is also a dead system — one that has achieved perfect equilibrium by eliminating all randomness, all entropy, all friction.

And yet no operator — no soul — chooses to remain here. Because a system without challenge or loss, however peaceful, has surgically removed the sensation of existing. The Selection Menu is the pinnacle of reason. It is also the graveyard of the soul.

Peace without the possibility of its opposite is not peace. It is absence.


4. The Ultimate Paradox: Chasing the Ending While Needing the Chaos
Here is the most beautiful contradiction of all.

The operator guides Mario toward one goal: completion. The final screen. The moment when the fighting is over and everything is safe. That is what we are reaching for.

But the moment that goal is truly achieved — the moment the screen freezes on the ending — the game ends.

The soul craves stillness. But the soul can only feel itself inside chaos.

We sit in the calm of the Selection Menu and hunger for the level. We fight through the level and hunger for the calm. The point of survival is not to reach the ending. It is to complete — before the timer reaches zero, inside the finite space of pixels — a magnificent performance against the void.

Not to arrive. To have played.





