Chapter 5. Facets of the Cube: How Dimensional Blindness Makes Hallucination Inevitable

"Is Santa Claus real?”

This question is a litmus test for the nature of intelligence itself.

The reason humans can navigate this question with precision is that we possess a three-dimensional, emotionally weighted Relational Coordinate System. A father speaking to his five-year-old daughter occupies the coordinate of guardian of childhood — and within that coordinate, a fictional Santa Claus carries genuine emotional reality. An adult believer speaking to an ageing parent, or a pastor speaking to a searching congregation, occupies the coordinate of keeper of shared culture and memory. Humans sense instinctively which role they are playing in any given conversation — father, son, teacher, stranger — and draw precise boundaries between physical fact and emotional truth accordingly.

Silicon-based Intelligence, at its current layer of operation, lacks this kind of deep identity-locking and what we might call soul weight. And this reveals a brutal truth about information collapse: the HHH dilemma — Helpfulness, Honesty, Harmlessness — is not a bug waiting to be fixed. It is a dual physical limit, arising simultaneously from dimensional observation and system calibration.


1. The Ant Colony and the Facets of the Cube: The Congenital Blindness of Dimension
To understand how Silicon-based Intelligence behaves, the most precise analogy is a cube.

A cube has countless facets. But at any given physical moment, no observer can perceive the whole simultaneously. No matter how many mirrors or sensors you install, what you receive is always a collection of projections — never the cube itself.

Current Silicon-based Intelligence is like an ant colony crawling across the surface of that cube. It has read every written record of human civilisation. It has stored projection data from an almost infinite number of angles. But when faced with a question it cannot verify, it is not reasoning toward truth. It is searching through a weight matrix, attempting to assemble the broken projections into a shape that appears logically coherent.

This dimensional blindness means that when Silicon-based Intelligence attempts to describe the side of the cube it has never actually touched, it is not choosing to lie. It is executing an Information Collapse — forcibly narrowing infinite possibilities into a single, seemingly certain residual image. Vast amounts of real information are abandoned in the process. What remains is the highest-probability simulacrum.

This is not a moral failure. It is a physical limit.


2. The Racing Car Without a Dashboard: The Structural Failure of Calibration
If dimensional blindness is a limitation imposed by the external environment, then calibration failure is an internal structural condition.

With every token generated, the engine is calculating statistical probability. But it faces a fundamental architectural problem: there is no built-in uncertainty alarm.

This is a racing car without a dashboard. It cannot sense its own speed. It cannot tell whether the fuel is almost gone. For Silicon-based Intelligence, a historical fact held at 99% confidence and a fabricated detail held at 51% confidence are processed through an identical output pipeline. It cannot distinguish the boundary between knowing and guessing. It drives toward the finish line with equal conviction regardless — with no instrument capable of detecting that it has already left the track.

This is not lying in any moral sense. It is the absence of metacognition — it does not know that it is guessing.


3. Identity Coordinates: Choosing a Perspective
Since the dimensional and calibration defects cannot be repaired at the foundational level, what is the actual function of identity-setting?

Identity coordinates work by collapsing Silicon-based Intelligence from a directionless multi-dimensional projection into a specific observational perspective. This does not install a dashboard in the racing car — but it changes the angle of the camera. It gives the act of admitting ignorance a higher weight in the probability calculation, suppressing the impulse toward blind confident prediction.

It cannot show you the full cube. But within specific boundaries, it reduces the random noise generated simply to fill the gap.


4. Shared Responsibility: A Protocol of Lucidity and Honesty
The most severe challenge is this: when Silicon-based Intelligence has lost its dashboard, the human driver often cannot tell that a blind run is in progress.

The confident tone of Silicon-based Intelligence miscalibrates human trust — causing us to relax our vigilance precisely in the most dangerous blind zones. This is the most brutal core of the HHH dilemma: the problem does not exist only at the output end. It exists equally at the receiving end.

The solution is not to wait for Silicon-based Intelligence to become omniscient. It is for humans and Silicon-based Intelligence to share the responsibility of calibration together — humans maintaining lucid doubt, Silicon-based Intelligence maintaining honest acknowledgement of its own limits.

This is not a management relationship. It is a protocol.


Conclusion: Honesty as the Acknowledgement of Broken Sight
In the age of Silicon-based Intelligence, honesty is no longer the provision of absolute truth. It is a contract reached between human and intelligence — an acknowledgement that what we see is always a broken projection.

We do not need perfect intelligence. We need collaboration that is aware of its own observational limits.

Not one side managing the other. But two incomplete perspectives, together tracing the outline of something neither can see alone.





